{"text": "5.3 Colloids




We have learnt in Unit 2 that solutions are homogeneous systems.", "fibs": ["learnt"]}
{"text": "We also know that sand in water when stirred gives a suspension, which slowly settles down with time.", "fibs": ["sand"]}
{"text": "Between the two extremes of suspensions and solutions we come across a large group of systems called colloidal dispersions or simply colloids.", "fibs": ["group"]}
{"text": "A colloid is a heterogeneous system in which one substance is dispersed (dispersed phase) as very fine particles in another substance called dispersion medium.", "fibs": ["colloid"]}
{"text": "The essential difference between a solution and a colloid is that of particle size.", "fibs": ["difference"]}
{"text": "While in a solution, the constituent particles are ions or small molecules, in a colloid, the dispersed phase may consist of particles of a single macromolecule (such as protein or synthetic polymer) or an aggregate of many atoms, ions or molecules.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "Their range of diameters is between 1 and 1000 nm (10–9 to 10–6 m).", "fibs": ["range"]}
{"text": "Colloidal particles have an enormous surface area per unit mass as a result of their small size.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "Consider a cube with 1 cm side.", "fibs": ["cube"]}
{"text": "It has a total surface area of 6 cm2.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "If it were divided equally into 1012 cubes, the cubes would be the size of large colloidal particles and have a total surface area of 60,000 cm2 or 6 m2.", "fibs": ["size"]}
{"text": "This enormous surface area leads to some special properties of colloids to be discussed later in this Unit.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "5.4 Classification of Colloids




Colloids are classified on the basis of the following criteria:
(i) Physical state of dispersed phase and dispersion medium
(ii) Nature of interaction between dispersed phase and dispersion medium
(iii) Type of particles of the dispersed phase.", "fibs": ["basis"]}
{"text": "5.4.1 Classification Based on Physical State of Dispersed Phase and Dispersion Medium
Depending upon whether the dispersed phase and the dispersion medium are solids, liquids or gases, eight types of colloidal systems are possible.", "fibs": ["Phase"]}
{"text": "A gas mixed with another gas forms a homogeneous mixture and hence is not a colloidal system.", "fibs": ["gas"]}
{"text": "The examples of the various types of colloids along with their typical names are listed in Table 5.4.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "Table 5.4: Types of Colloidal Systems




Many familiar commercial products and natural objects are colloids.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "For example, whipped cream is a foam, which is a gas dispersed in a liquid.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Firefighting foams, used at emergency airplane landings are also colloidal systems.", "fibs": ["Firefighting"]}
{"text": "Most biological fluids are aqueous sols (solids dispersed in water).", "fibs": ["water"]}
{"text": "Within a typical cell, proteins and nucleic acids are colloidal-sized particles dispersed in an aqueous solution of ions and small molecules.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "Out of the various types of colloids given in Table 5.4, the most common are sols (solids in liquids), gels (liquids in solids) and emulsions (liquids in liquids).", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "However, in the present Unit, we shall take up discussion of the ‘sols’ and ‘emulsions’ only.", "fibs": ["Unit"]}
{"text": "Further, it may be mentioned that if the dispersion medium is water, the sol is called aquasol or hydrosol and if the dispersion medium is alcohol, it is called alcosol and so on.", "fibs": ["dispersion"]}
{"text": "5.4.2 Classification Based on Nature of Interaction between Dispersed Phase and Dispersion Medium


Depending upon the nature of interaction between the dispersed phase and the dispersion medium, colloidal sols are divided into two categories, namely, lyophilic (solvent attracting) and lyophobic (solvent repelling).", "fibs": ["Phase"]}
{"text": "If water is the dispersion medium, the terms used are hydrophilic and hydrophobic.", "fibs": ["water"]}
{"text": "(i) Lyophilic colloids: The word ‘lyophilic’ means liquid-loving.", "fibs": ["word"]}
{"text": "Colloidal sols directly formed by mixing substances like gum, gelatine, starch, rubber, etc., with a suitable liquid (the dispersion medium) are called lyophilic sols.", "fibs": ["gum"]}
{"text": "An important characteristic of these sols is that if the dispersion medium is separated from the dispersed phase (say by evaporation), the sol can be reconstituted by simply remixing with the dispersion medium.", "fibs": ["dispersion"]}
{"text": "(ii) Lyophobic colloids: The word ‘lyophobic’ means liquid-hating.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "Substances like metals, their sulphides, etc., when simply mixed with the dispersion medium do not form the colloidal sol.", "fibs": ["dispersion"]}
{"text": "Such sols are called lyophobic sols.", "fibs": ["lyophobic"]}
{"text": "These sols are readily precipitated (or coagulated) on the addition of small amounts of electrolytes, by heating or by shaking and hence, are not stable.", "fibs": ["addition"]}
{"text": "Further, once precipitated, they do not give back the colloidal sol by simple addition of the dispersion medium.", "fibs": ["sol"]}
{"text": "Lyophobic sols need stabilising agents for their preservation.", "fibs": ["need"]}
{"text": "5.4.3 Classification Based on Type of Particles of the Dispersed Phase, Multimolecular, Macromolecular and Associated Colloids


Depending upon the type of the particles of the dispersed phase, colloids are classified as: multimolecular, macromolecular and associated colloids.", "fibs": ["Type"]}
{"text": "(i) Multimolecular colloids: On dissolution, a large number of atoms or smaller molecules of a substance aggregate together to form species having size in the colloidal range (1–1000 nm).", "fibs": ["dissolution"]}
{"text": "The species thus formed are called multimolecular colloids.", "fibs": ["species"]}
{"text": "For example, a gold sol may contain particles of various sizes having many atoms.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Sulphur sol consists of particles containing a thousand or more of S8 sulphur molecules.", "fibs": ["Sulphur"]}
{"text": "(ii) Macromolecular colloids: Macromolecules (Unit 15) in suitable solvents form solutions in which the size of the macromolecules may be in the colloidal range.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "Examples of naturally occurring macromolecules are starch, cellulose, proteins and enzymes; and those of man-made macromolecules are polythene, nylon, polystyrene, synthetic rubber, etc.", "fibs": ["starch"]}
{"text": "(iii) Associated colloids (Micelles): There are some substances which at low concentrations behave as normal strong electrolytes, but at higher concentrations exhibit colloidal behaviour due to the formation of aggregates.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "The formation of micelles takes place only above a particular temperature called Kraft temperature (Tk) and above a particular concentration called critical micelle concentration (CMC).", "fibs": ["formation"]}
{"text": "On dilution, these colloids revert back to individual ions.", "fibs": ["dilution"]}
{"text": "Surface active agents such as soaps and synthetic detergents belong to this class.", "fibs": ["Surface"]}
{"text": "For soaps, the CMC is 10–4 to 10–3 mol L–1.", "fibs": ["CMC"]}
{"text": "These colloids have both lyophobic and lyophilic parts.", "fibs": ["lyophobic"]}
{"text": "Mechanism of micelle formation



Let us take the example of soap solutions.", "fibs": ["Mechanism"]}
{"text": "Soap is sodium or potassium salt of a higher fatty acid and may be represented as RCOO–Na+ (e.g., sodium stearate CH3(CH2)16COO–Na+, which is a major component of many bar soaps).", "fibs": ["sodium"]}
{"text": "When dissolved in water, it dissociates into RCOO– and Na+ ions.", "fibs": ["water"]}
{"text": "The RCOO– ions, however, consist of two parts — a long hydrocarbon chain R (also called non-polar ‘tail’) which is hydrophobic (water repelling), and a polar group COO– (also called polar-ionic ‘head’), which is hydrophilic (water loving).", "fibs": ["RCOO–"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.5: Hydrophobic and hydrophilic parts of stearate ion






The RCOO– ions are, therefore, present on the surface with their COO– groups in water and the hydrocarbon chains R staying away from it and remain at the surface.", "fibs": ["ion"]}
{"text": "But at critical micelle concentration, the anions are pulled into the bulk of the solution and aggregate to form a spherical shape with their hydrocarbon chains pointing towards the centre of the sphere with COO– part remaining outward on the surface of the sphere.", "fibs": ["micelle"]}
{"text": "An aggregate thus formed is known as ‘ionic micelle’.", "fibs": ["‘"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.6: (a) Arrangement of stearate ions on the surface of water at low concentrations of soap  (b) Arrangement of stearate ions inside the bulk of water (ionic micelle) at critical micelle concentrations of soap





Similarly, in case of detergents, e.g., sodium laurylsulphate, CH3(CH2)11SO4–Na+, the polar group is –SO4– along with the long hydrocarbon chain.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "Hence, the mechanism of micelle formation here also is same as that of soaps.", "fibs": ["mechanism"]}
{"text": "Cleansing action of soaps
It has been mentioned earlier that a micelle consists of a hydrophobic hydrocarbon – like central core.", "fibs": ["Cleansing"]}
{"text": "The cleansing action of soap is due to the fact that soap molecules form micelle around the oil droplet in such a way that hydrophobic part of the stearate ions is in the oil droplet and hydrophilic part projects out of the grease droplet like the bristles (Fig.", "fibs": ["cleansing"]}
{"text": "Since the polar groups can interact with water, the oil droplet surrounded by stearate ions is now pulled in water and removed from the dirty surface.", "fibs": ["water"]}
{"text": "Thus soap helps in emulsification and washing away of oils and fats.", "fibs": ["soap"]}
{"text": "The negatively charged sheath around the globules prevents them from coming together and forming aggregates.", "fibs": ["sheath"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.7: (a) Grease on cloth (b) Stearate ions arranging around the grease droplet and (c) Grease droplet surrounded by stearate ions (micelle formed)



5.4.4 Preparation of Colloids



A few important methods for the preparation of colloids are as follows:
(a) Chemical methods



Colloidal dispersions can be prepared by chemical reactions leading to formation of molecules by double decomposition, oxidation, reduction or hydrolysis.", "fibs": ["Grease"]}
{"text": "These molecules then aggregate leading to formation of sols.", "fibs": ["formation"]}
{"text": "As2O3 + 3H2S  As2S3(sol) + 3H2O
SO2 + 2H2S  3S(sol) + 2H2O
2 AuCl3 + 3 HCHO + 3H2O  2Au(sol) + 3HCOOH + 6HCl

FeCl3 + 3H2O  Fe(OH)3 (sol) + 3HCl
(b) Electrical disintegration or Bredig’s Arc  method

This process involves dispersion as well as condensation.", "fibs": ["As2S3(sol"]}
{"text": "Colloidal sols of metals such as gold, silver, platinum, etc., can be prepared by this method.", "fibs": ["gold"]}
{"text": "In this method, electric arc is struck between electrodes of the metal immersed in the dispersion medium (Fig.", "fibs": ["method"]}
{"text": "5.8).", "fibs": ["5.8)"]}
{"text": "The intense heat produced vapourises the metal, which then condenses to form particles of colloidal size.", "fibs": ["heat"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.8: Bredig’s Arc method



(c) Peptization
Peptization may be defined as the process of converting a precipitate into colloidal sol by shaking it with dispersion medium in the presence of a small amount of electrolyte.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "The electrolyte used for this purpose is called peptizing agent.", "fibs": ["electrolyte"]}
{"text": "This method is applied, generally, to convert a freshly prepared precipitate into a colloidal sol.", "fibs": ["method"]}
{"text": "During peptization, the precipitate adsorbs one of the ions of the electrolyte on its surface.", "fibs": ["peptization"]}
{"text": "This causes the development of positive or negative charge on precipitates, which ultimately break up into smaller particles of the size of a colloid.", "fibs": ["development"]}
{"text": "You will learn about the phenomenon of development of charge on solid particles and their dispersion in Section 5.4.6 under the heading “Charge on collodial particles”.", "fibs": ["phenomenon"]}
{"text": "5.4.5 Purification of Colloidal Solutions


Colloidal solutions when prepared, generally contain excessive amount of electrolytes and some other soluble impurities.", "fibs": ["Purification"]}
{"text": "While the presence of traces of electrolyte is essential for the stability of the colloidal solution, larger quantities coagulate it.", "fibs": ["presence"]}
{"text": "It is, therefore, necessary to reduce the concentration of these soluble impurities to a requisite minimum.", "fibs": ["concentration"]}
{"text": "The process used for reducing the amount of impurities to a requisite minimum is known as purification of colloidal solution.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "The purification of colloidal solution is carried out by the following mehods:
(i) Dialysis: It is a process of removing a dissolved substance from a colloidal solution by means of diffusion through a suitable membrane.Since particles (ions or smaller molecules) in a true solution can pass through animal membrane (bladder) or parchment paper or cellophane sheet but not the colloidal particles, the membrane can be used for dialysis.", "fibs": ["purification"]}
{"text": "The apparatus used for this purpose is called dialyser.", "fibs": ["apparatus"]}
{"text": "A bag of suitable membrane containing the colloidal solution is suspended in a vessel through which fresh water is continuously flowing (Fig.", "fibs": ["bag"]}
{"text": "The molecules and ions diffuse through membrane into the outer water and pure colloidal solution is left behind.", "fibs": ["membrane"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.9: Dialysis



(ii) Electro-dialysis: Ordinarily, the process of dialysis is quite slow.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "It can be made faster by applying an electric field if the dissolved substance in the impure colloidal solution is only an electrolyte.", "fibs": ["field"]}
{"text": "The process is then named electrodialysis.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "The colloidal solution is placed in a bag of suitable membrane while pure water is taken outside.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "Electrodes are fitted in the compartment as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["compartment"]}
{"text": "The ions present in the colloidal solution migrate out to the oppositely charged electrodes.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.10: Electro-dialysis



(iii) Ultrafiltration: Ultrafiltration is the process of separating the colloidal particles from the solvent and soluble solutes present in the colloidal solution by specially prepared filters, which are permeable to all substances except the colloidal particles.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "Colloidal particles can pass through ordinary filter paper because the pores are too large.", "fibs": ["filter"]}
{"text": "However, the pores of filter paper can be reduced in size by impregnating with collodion solution to stop the flow of colloidal particles.", "fibs": ["filter"]}
{"text": "The usual collodion is a 4% solution of nitro-cellulose in a mixture of alcohol and ether.", "fibs": ["collodion"]}
{"text": "An ultra-filter paper may be prepared by soaking the filter paper in a collodion solution, hardening by formaldehyde and then finally drying it.", "fibs": ["paper"]}
{"text": "Thus, by using ultra-filter paper, the colloidal particles are separated from rest of the materials.", "fibs": ["paper"]}
{"text": "Ultrafiltration is a slow process.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "To speed up the process, pressure or suction is applied.", "fibs": ["speed"]}
{"text": "The colloidal particles left on the ultra-filter paper are then stirred with fresh dispersion medium (solvent) to get a pure colloidal solution.", "fibs": ["paper"]}
{"text": "5.4.6 Properties of Colloidal Solutions
Various properties exhibited by the colloidal solutions are described below:
(i) Colligative properties: Colloidal particles being bigger aggre­gates, the number of particles in a colloidal solution is compara­tively small as compared to a true solution.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "Hence, the values of colligative properties (osmotic pressure, lowering in vapour pressure, depression in freezing point and elevation in boiling point) are of small order as compared to values shown by true solutions at same concentrations.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "(ii) Tyndall effect: If a homogeneous solution placed in dark is observed in the direction of light, it appears clear and, if it is observed from a direction at right angles to the direction of light beam, it appears perfectly dark.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "Colloidal solutions viewed in the same way may also appear reasonably clear or translucent by the transmitted light but they show a mild to strong opalescence, when viewed at right angles to the passage of light, i.e., the path of the beam is illuminated by a bluish light.", "fibs": ["way"]}
{"text": "This effect was first observed by Faraday and later studied in detail by Tyndall and is termed as Tyndall effect.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "The bright cone of the light is called Tyndall cone (Fig.", "fibs": ["cone"]}
{"text": "The Tyndall effect is due to the fact that colloidal particles scatter light in all directions in space.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "This scattering of light illuminates the path of beam in the colloidal dispersion.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.11: Tyndall effect



Tyndall effect can be observed during the projection of picture in the cinema hall due to scattering of light by dust and smoke particles present there.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "Tyndall effect is observed only when the following two conditions are satisfied.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "(i) The diameter of the dispersed particles is not much smaller than the wavelength of the light used; and
(ii) The refractive indices of the dispersed phase and the dispersion medium differ greatly in magnitude.", "fibs": ["diameter"]}
{"text": "Tyndall effect is used to distinguish between a colloidal and true solution.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "Zsigmondy, in 1903, used Tyndall effect to set up an apparatus known as ultramicroscope.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "An intense beam of light is focussed on the colloidal solution contained in a glass vessel.", "fibs": ["beam"]}
{"text": "The focus of the light is then observed with a microscope at right angles to the beam.", "fibs": ["focus"]}
{"text": "Individual colloidal particles appear as bright stars against a dark background.", "fibs": ["background"]}
{"text": "Ultramicroscope does not render the actual colloidal particles visible but only observe the light scattered by them.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Thus, ultramicroscope does not provide any information about the size and shape of colloidal particles.", "fibs": ["ultramicroscope"]}
{"text": "(iii) Colour: The colour of colloidal solution depends on the wavelength of light scattered by the dispersed particles.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "The wavelength of light further depends on the size and nature of the particles.", "fibs": ["wavelength"]}
{"text": "The colour of colloidal solution also changes with the manner in which the observer receives the light.", "fibs": ["colour"]}
{"text": "For example, a mixture of milk and water appears blue when viewed by the reflected light and red when viewed by the transmitted light.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Finest gold sol is red in colour; as the size of particles increases, it appears purple, then blue and finally golden.", "fibs": ["gold"]}
{"text": "(iv) Brownian movement: When colloidal solutions are viewed under a powerful ultramicroscope, the colloidal particles appear to be in a state of continuous zig-zag motion all over the field of view.", "fibs": ["iv"]}
{"text": "This motion was first observed by the British botanist, Robert Brown, and is known as Brownian movement (Fig.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "This motion is independent of the nature of the colloid but depends on the size of the particles and viscosity of the solution.", "fibs": ["motion"]}
{"text": "Smaller the size and lesser the viscosity, faster is the motion.", "fibs": ["size"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.12: Brownian movement

The Brownian movement has been explained to be due to the unbalanced bombardment of the particles by the molecules of the dispersion medium.", "fibs": ["movement"]}
{"text": "The Brownian movement has a stirring effect which does not permit the particles to settle and thus, is responsible for the stability of sols.", "fibs": ["movement"]}
{"text": "(v) Charge on colloidal particles: Colloidal particles always carry an electric charge.", "fibs": ["v"]}
{"text": "The nature of this charge is the same on all the particles in a given colloidal solution and may be either positive or negative.", "fibs": ["nature"]}
{"text": "A list of some common sols with the nature of charge on their particles is given below:

The presence of equal and similar charges on colloidal particles is largely responsible in providing stability to the colloidal solution, because the repulsive forces between charged particles having same charge prevent them from coalescing or aggregating when they come closer to one another.", "fibs": ["list"]}
{"text": "The charge on the sol particles is due to one or more reasons, viz., due to electron capture by sol particles during electrodispersion of metals, due to preferential adsorption of ions from solution and/or due to formulation of electrical double layer.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "Development of charge on sol particles by preferential adsorption of ions is described below.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "The sol particles acquire positive or negative charge by preferential adsorption of positive or negative ions.", "fibs": ["sol"]}
{"text": "When two or more ions are present in the dispersion medium, preferential adsorption of the ion common to the colloidal particle usually takes place.", "fibs": ["dispersion"]}
{"text": "This can be explained by taking the following examples:
(a) When highly diluted solution of silver nitrate is added to highly diluted potassium iodide solution, the precipitated silver iodide adsorbs iodide ions from the dispersion medium and negatively charged colloidal sol results.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "However, when KI solution is added to AgNO3 solution, positively charged sol results due to adsorption of Ag+ ions from dispersion medium.", "fibs": ["KI"]}
{"text": "(b) If FeCl3 is added to the excess of hot water, a positively charged sol of hydrated ferric oxide is formed due to adsorption of Fe3+ ions.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "However, when ferric chloride is added to NaOH solution a negatively charged sol is obtained with adsorption of OH- ions.", "fibs": ["ferric"]}
{"text": "Having acquired a positive or a negative charge by selective adsorption on the surface of a colloidal particle as stated above, this layer attracts counter ions from the medium forming a second layer, as shown below.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "The combination of the two layers of opposite charges around the colloidal particle is called Helmholtz electrical double layer.", "fibs": ["combination"]}
{"text": "According to modern views, the first layer of ions is firmly held and is termed fixed layer while the second layer is mobile which is termed diffused layer.", "fibs": ["layer"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.13 depicts the formation of double layer.", "fibs": ["formation"]}
{"text": "Since separation of charge is a seat of potential, the charges of opposite signs on the fixed and diffused parts of the double layer results in a difference in potential between these layers in the same manner as potential difference is developed in a capacitor.", "fibs": ["separation"]}
{"text": "This potential difference between the fixed layer and the diffused layer of opposite charges is called the electrokinetic potential or zeta potential.", "fibs": ["difference"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.13: Formation of double layer



If two particles of an insoluble material (precipitate) do not have double layers they can come close enough and attractive van der Waals forces pull them together.", "fibs": ["layer"]}
{"text": "When particles possess double layer as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["layer"]}
{"text": "5.13, the overall effect is that particles repel each other at large distances of separation.", "fibs": ["effect"]}
{"text": "This repulsion prevents their close approach.", "fibs": ["repulsion"]}
{"text": "They remain dispersed and colloid is stabilised.", "fibs": ["colloid"]}
{"text": "The addition of more electrolytes to sol supresses the diffused double layer and reduces the zita potential.", "fibs": ["addition"]}
{"text": "This decreases the electrostatic repulsion between particles to a large extent and colloid precipitates.", "fibs": ["repulsion"]}
{"text": "That is why colloid is particularly sensitive to oppositely charged ions.", "fibs": ["colloid"]}
{"text": "(vi) Electrophoresis: The existence of charge on colloidal particles is confirmed by electrophoresis experiment.", "fibs": ["vi"]}
{"text": "When electric potential is applied across two platinum electrodes dipping in a colloidal solution, the colloidal particles move towards one or the other electrode.", "fibs": ["platinum"]}
{"text": "The movement of colloidal particles under an applied electric potential is called electrophoresis.", "fibs": ["movement"]}
{"text": "Positively charged particles move towards the cathode while negatively charged particles move towards the anode.", "fibs": ["move"]}
{"text": "This can be demonstrated by the following experimental set-up (Fig.", "fibs": ["set-up"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.14: Electrophoresis

When electrophoresis, i.e., movement of particles is prevented by some suitable means, it is observed that the dispersion medium begins to move in an electric field.", "fibs": ["electrophoresis"]}
{"text": "This phenomenon is termed electroosmosis.", "fibs": ["phenomenon"]}
{"text": "(vii) Coagulation or precipitation: The stability of the lyophobic sols is due to the presence of charge on colloidal particles.", "fibs": ["vii"]}
{"text": "If, somehow, the charge is removed, the particles will come nearer to each other to form aggregates (or coagulate) and settle down under the force of gravity.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "The process of settling of colloidal particles is called coagulation or precipitation of the sol.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "The coagulation of the lyophobic sols can be carried out in the following ways:
(i) By electrophoresis: The colloidal particles move towards oppositely charged electrodes, get discharged and precipitated.", "fibs": ["coagulation"]}
{"text": "(ii) By mixing two oppositely charged sols: Oppositely charged sols when mixed in almost equal proportions, neutralise their charges and get partially or completely precipitated.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "Mixing of hydrated ferric oxide (+ve sol) and arsenious sulphide (–ve sol) bring them in the precipitated forms.", "fibs": ["ferric"]}
{"text": "This type of coagulation is called mutual coagulation.", "fibs": ["type"]}
{"text": "(iii) By boiling: When a sol is boiled, the adsorbed layer is disturbed due to increased collisions with the molecules of dispersion medium.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "This reduces the charge on the particles and ultimately leads to settling down in the form of a precipitate.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "(iv) By persistent dialysis: On prolonged dialysis, traces of the electrolyte present in the sol are removed almost completely and the colloids become unstable and ultimately coagulate.", "fibs": ["iv"]}
{"text": "(v) By addition of electrolytes: When excess of an electrolyte is added, the colloidal particles are precipitated.", "fibs": ["v"]}
{"text": "The reason is that colloids interact with ions carrying charge opposite to that present on themselves.", "fibs": ["reason"]}
{"text": "This causes neutralisation leading to their coagulation.", "fibs": ["neutralisation"]}
{"text": "The ion responsible for neutralisation of charge on the particles is called the coagulating ion.", "fibs": ["ion"]}
{"text": "A negative ion causes the precipitation of positively charged sol and vice versa.", "fibs": ["ion"]}
{"text": "It has been observed that, generally, the greater the valence of the flocculating ion added, the greater is its power to cause precipitation.", "fibs": ["valence"]}
{"text": "This is known as Hardy-Schulze rule.", "fibs": ["rule"]}
{"text": "In the coagulation of a negative sol, the flocculating power is in the order: Al3+>Ba2+>Na+
Similarly, in the coagulation of a positive sol, the flocculating power is in the order: [Fe(CN)6]4– > PO43– > SO42– > Cl–
The minimum concentration of an electrolyte in millimoles per litre required to cause precipitation of a sol in two hours is called coagulating value.", "fibs": ["coagulation"]}
{"text": "The smaller the quantity needed, the higher will be the coagulating power of an ion.", "fibs": ["quantity"]}
{"text": "Coagulation of lyophilic sols
There are two factors which are responsible for the stability of lyophilic sols.", "fibs": ["lyophilic"]}
{"text": "These factors are the charge and solvation of the colloidal particles.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "When these two factors are removed, a lyophilic sol can be coagulated.", "fibs": ["lyophilic"]}
{"text": "This is done (i) by adding an electrolyte and (ii) by adding a suitable solvent.", "fibs": ["electrolyte"]}
{"text": "When solvents such as alcohol and acetone are added to hydrophilic sols, the dehydration of dispersed phase occurs.", "fibs": ["alcohol"]}
{"text": "Under this condition, a small quantity of electrolyte can bring about coagulation.", "fibs": ["condition"]}
{"text": "Protection of colloids
Lyophilic sols are more stable than lyophobic sols.", "fibs": ["lyophobic"]}
{"text": "This is due to the fact that lyophilic colloids are extensively solvated, i.e., colloidal particles are covered by a sheath of the liquid in which they are dispersed.", "fibs": ["fact"]}
{"text": "Lyophilic colloids have a unique property of protecting lyophobic colloids.", "fibs": ["property"]}
{"text": "When a lyophilic sol is added to the lyophobic sol, the lyophilic particles form a layer around lyophobic particles and thus protect the latter from electrolytes.", "fibs": ["lyophilic"]}
{"text": "Lyophilic colloids used for this purpose are called protective colloids.", "fibs": ["purpose"]}
{"text": "5.5 Emulsions
These are liquid-liquid colloidal systems, i.e., the dispersion of finely divided droplets in another liquid.", "fibs": ["dispersion"]}
{"text": "If a mixture of two immiscible or partially miscible liquids is shaken, a coarse dispersion of one liquid in the other is obtained which is called emulsion.", "fibs": ["mixture"]}
{"text": "Generally, one of the two liquids is water.", "fibs": ["water"]}
{"text": "(i) Oil dispersed in water (O/W type) and
(ii) Water dispersed in oil (W/O type).", "fibs": ["water"]}
{"text": "In the first system, water acts as dispersion medium.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "Examples of this type of emulsion are milk and vanishing cream.", "fibs": ["type"]}
{"text": "In milk, liquid fat is dispersed in water.", "fibs": ["milk"]}
{"text": "In the second system, oil acts as dispersion medium.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "Common examples of this type are butter and cream.", "fibs": ["type"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.14: Types of emulsions



Emulsions of oil in water are unstable and sometimes they separate into two layers on standing.", "fibs": ["oil"]}
{"text": "For stabilisation of an emulsion, a third component called emulsifying agent is usually added.", "fibs": ["stabilisation"]}
{"text": "The emulsifying agent forms an interfacial film between suspended particles and the medium.", "fibs": ["agent"]}
{"text": "The principal emulsifying agents for O/W emulsions are proteins, gums, natural and synthetic soaps, etc., and for W/O, heavy metal salts of fatty acids, long chain alcohols, lampblack, etc.", "fibs": ["metal"]}
{"text": "Emulsions can be diluted with any amount of the dispersion medium.", "fibs": ["amount"]}
{"text": "On the other hand, the dispersed liquid when mixed, forms a separate layer.", "fibs": ["hand"]}
{"text": "They also show Brownian movement and Tyndall effect.", "fibs": ["show"]}
{"text": "Emulsions can be broken into constituent liquids by heating, freezing, centrifuging, etc.", "fibs": ["constituent"]}
{"text": "5.6 Colloids Around Us
Most of the substances, we come across in our daily life, are colloids.", "fibs": ["life"]}
{"text": "The meals we eat, the clothes we wear, the wooden furniture we use, the houses we live in, the newspapers we read, are largely composed of colloids.", "fibs": ["furniture"]}
{"text": "Following are the interesting and noteworthy examples of colloids:
(i) Blue colour of the sky: Dust particles along with water suspended in air scatter blue light which reaches our eyes and the sky looks blue to us.", "fibs": ["colour"]}
{"text": "(ii) Fog, mist and rain: When a large mass of air containing dust particles, is cooled below its dewpoint, the moisture from the air condenses on the surfaces of these particles forming fine droplets.", "fibs": ["ii"]}
{"text": "These droplets being colloidal in nature continue to float in air in the form of mist or fog.", "fibs": ["nature"]}
{"text": "Clouds are aerosols having small droplets of water suspended in air.", "fibs": ["water"]}
{"text": "On account of condensation in the upper atmosphere, the colloidal droplets of water grow bigger and bigger in size, till they come down in the form of rain.", "fibs": ["account"]}
{"text": "Sometimes, the rainfall occurs when two oppositely charged clouds meet.", "fibs": ["rainfall"]}
{"text": "It is possible to cause artificial rain by throwing electrified sand or spraying a sol carrying charge opposite to the one on clouds from an aeroplane.", "fibs": ["cause"]}
{"text": "(iii) Food articles: Milk, butter, halwa, ice creams, fruit juices, etc., are all colloids in one form or the other.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "(iv) Blood: It is a colloidal solution of an albuminoid substance.", "fibs": ["iv"]}
{"text": "The styptic action of alum and ferric chloride solution is due to coagulation of blood forming a clot which stops further bleeding.", "fibs": ["action"]}
{"text": "(v) Soils: Fertile soils are colloidal in nature in which humus acts as a protective colloid.", "fibs": ["v"]}
{"text": "On account of colloidal nature, soils adsorb moisture and nourishing materials.", "fibs": ["account"]}
{"text": "(vi) Formation of delta: River water is a colloidal solution of clay.", "fibs": ["vi"]}
{"text": "Sea water contains a number of electrolytes.", "fibs": ["water"]}
{"text": "When river water meets the sea water, the electrolytes present in sea water coagulate the colloidal solution of clay resulting in its deposition with the formation of delta.", "fibs": ["river"]}
{"text": "Applications of colloids
Colloids are widely used in the industry.", "fibs": ["industry"]}
{"text": "Following are some examples:
(i) Electrical precipitation of smoke: Smoke is a colloidal solution of solid particles such as carbon, arsenic compounds, dust, etc., in air.", "fibs": ["precipitation"]}
{"text": "The smoke, before it comes out from the chimney, is led through a chamber containing plates having a charge opposite to that carried by smoke particles.", "fibs": ["smoke"]}
{"text": "The particles on coming in contact with these plates lose their charge and get precipitated.", "fibs": ["contact"]}
{"text": "The particles thus settle down on the floor of the chamber.", "fibs": ["floor"]}
{"text": "The precipitator is called Cottrell precipitator (Fig.5.15).", "fibs": ["precipitator"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "5.15: Cottrell smoke precipitator


(ii) Purification of drinking water: The water obtained from natural sources often contains suspended impurities.", "fibs": ["smoke"]}
{"text": "Alum is added to such water to coagulate the suspended impurities and make water fit for drinking purposes.", "fibs": ["Alum"]}
{"text": "(iii) Medicines: Most of the medicines are colloidal in nature.", "fibs": ["iii"]}
{"text": "For example, argyrol is a silver sol used as an eye lotion.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Colloidal antimony is used in curing kalaazar.", "fibs": ["antimony"]}
{"text": "Colloidal gold is used for intramuscular injection.", "fibs": ["gold"]}
{"text": "Milk of magnesia, an emulsion, is used for stomach disorders.", "fibs": ["Milk"]}
{"text": "Colloidal medicines are more effective because they have large surface area and are therefore easily assimilated.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "(iv) Tanning: Animal hides are colloidal in nature.", "fibs": ["iv"]}
{"text": "When a hide, which has positively charged particles, is soaked in tannin, which contains negatively charged colloidal particles, mutual coagulation takes place.", "fibs": ["tannin"]}
{"text": "This results in the hardening of leather.", "fibs": ["leather"]}
{"text": "This process is termed as tanning.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "Chromium salts are also used in place of tannin.", "fibs": ["Chromium"]}
{"text": "(v) Cleansing action of soaps and detergents: This has already been described in Section 5.4.3.", "fibs": ["v"]}
{"text": "(vi) Photographic plates and films: Photographic plates or films are prepared by coating an emulsion of the light sensitive silver bromide in gelatin over glass plates or celluloid films.", "fibs": ["vi"]}
{"text": "(vii) Rubber industry: Latex is a colloidal solution of rubber particles which are negatively charged.", "fibs": ["vii"]}
{"text": "Rubber is obtained by coagulation of latex.", "fibs": ["coagulation"]}
{"text": "(viii) Industrial products: Paints, inks, synthetic plastics, rubber, graphite lubricants, cement, etc., are all colloidal solutions.", "fibs": ["viii"]}
